x86-64 Linux ptrace-based memory scanner: parses /proc/<pid>/maps, attaches via PTRACE_ATTACH, performs AOB pattern matching with ?? wildcards using PEEKDATA, and generates pointer maps to target regions.

HOW TO USE THE CODE

sudo ./memory_scanner 12345 aob "DE AD BE EF ?? 11 22"
sudo ./memory_scanner 12345 pointer 0x7f8abc000000

PEEKDATA mechanics explaination

PTRACE_PEEKDATA mechanics (Linux x86-64):
ptrace(PTRACE_PEEKDATA, pid, addr, NULL) is a ptrace(2) request that reads a machine word (8 bytes on x86-64) from the tracee's virtual memory at addr.
Kernel-side flow:
Tracee attachment — Requires prior PTRACE_ATTACH + wait4().
Address validation — Kernel checks addr is a valid userspace mapping in the tracee's mm.
Page table walk — Translates addr → physical page via tracee's mm->pgd.
Copy — Uses copy_from_user() (or direct access in same mm context) to fetch the 64-bit word into a kernel buffer.
Return — Value returned directly in rax of the tracer's syscall (no data param used for PEEK).

In the code I wrote;

mov rax, 101          ; __NR_ptrace
mov rdi, 2            ; PTRACE_PEEKDATA
mov rsi, [pid]
mov rdx, rbx          ; target virtual address
xor r10, r10
syscall
; rax now contains *(uint64_t*)addr from target process

This is the core primitive enabling external memory inspection without injecting code.


